According to Section 8.7 of Canadian Aviation Regulations, if a pilot experiences a communication failure, they should:

(a) Select the transponder to reply to Mode A/3 Code 7600 in the absence of an assigned route or route that ATC has advised may be expected in a further clearance.

(b) Altitude: At the highest of the following altitudes or FLs depicted in the procedure, and intercepting the final approach course for a straight-in approach;

According to Section 2.3.1 of Canadian Aviation Regulations:

(a) For the purpose of a police operation that is conducted in the service of a police authority;
(b) for the purpose of saving human life;
(c) for fire-fighting or air ambulance operations;

VFR cruising altitudes for westbound flights are specified as follows:

* At more than 3,000 ft AGL (Section 2.3.1(a))
* In accordance with VFR (Section 2.3.1(b))

These altitudes apply to all types of westbound flights, including police operations and saving human life or fire-fighting/air ambulance operations.
